    221 Loads, Constraints, Case Control, and Parameters in Static Analysis Main Index External Superelement Load Labeling Introduction This enhancement will allow the user to more easily identify, select, and even scale, the load cases from an external superelement creation run. In the external superelement creation run, the number of loads is determined by the number of subcases. The following scenario shows mapping of the load cases when the external superelement creation run has fewer load case(s) than the assembly run with static analysis. In the assembly run’s subcase 401, there will be no contribution from the external superelement. The following scenario shows the mapping of the load cases when the external superelement creation run has more load case(s) than the assembly run. In the assembly run, external superelement’s subcase 40 will be ignored. User Warning Message 4588 will be issued in both scenarios above. In order to avoid these situations, the user must specify the proper number of subcases in static assembly run or proper number of EXCITEIDs in a dynamic assembly run a priori.

    Superelements and Modules User’s Guide External Superelement Load Labeling222 Main Index Benefits This enhancement gives the user the ability to de-select, re-sequence, or scale the loads coming from the external superelement and avoid User Warning Message 4588. User Interface The user interface includes the LDLABEL Case Control command to be specified in the external superelement creation run and the SELOAD Bulk Data entry in the assembly run. The LDLABEL command is optional and may be used to define a string of 64 characters to a SUBCASE in the external superelement creation run. The following shows example usage in two creation runs. If the LDLABEL is specified in any subcase but not all subcases then the following defaults will be applied to those subcases without LDLABEL in the following order: 1.LABEL inside the subcase 2.If no LABEL, then SUBTITLE inside the subcase 3.If no SUBTITLE, then TITLE inside the subcase It should be noted that the program will automatically create an internal METADATA table with the LDLABEL and SUBCASE information which will be written to the .pch file if one of the following keywords is specified: EXTBULK, DMIGOP2, DMIGPCH, or MATOP4. For example, the following Case Control commands: SUBCASE 10 LDLABEL=Z FORCE ON 825 LOAD=1000 SUBCASE 20 LDLABEL=Z FORCE ON 836 LOAD=2000 SUBCASE 30 LDLABEL=Z FORCE ON 812 LOAD=3000

    223 Loads, Constraints, Case Control, and Parameters in Static Analysis Main Index will produce the following METADATA entry in the .pch file: METADATAXSLDLBL:100 10 1000 Z FORCE ON 825 20 2000 Z FORCE ON 836 30 3000 Z FORCE ON 812 Also, if DMIGDB, MATDB, or DMIGOP2 are specified, the same information will be written to an internal table called XSLDLBL which is then exported to the database or op2 file. The METADATA entry is only required for the DMIGPCH or MATOP4 export options. If it is desired that the default logic is to be applied to all subcases then specify LDLABEL with no argument above all subcases. Then in the static analysis assembly run three subcases are defined along with the new SELOAD Bulk Data entries to select and scale the desired columns from above. The SELOAD entry is requested by the LOAD Case Control command and the parent entry also specifies an overall scale factor to be applied to all superelement subcases. Then the SELOAD contains any number of continuations which select the

    Superelements and Modules User’s Guide External Superelement Load Labeling224 Main Index superelement, its load case, and a scale factor. Note that the LOAD=33 includes no loads from superelement 200. In a dynamic analysis the loads are defined on RLOADi and TLOADi Bulk Data entries and linked to static load cases by the EXCITED field. Therefore, the SELOAD entry references EXCITEID instead of “n” on the LOAD Case Control command. Guidelines and Limitations The LOAD Bulk Data entry will not combine SELOAD Bulk Data entries. Thermal Loads in Static Analysis Thermal loads must also be partitioned and associated to the appropriate superelement dof in order to obtain
    correct results. In statics, the thermal load is converted to forces at grids points by assuming a ‘fixed wall’.
    For example, a simple rod element subjected to thermal loads will have equivalent mechanical forces calculated by the following: Calculate the thermal strains (4-15) Calculate the thermal stresses for fixed grid (4-16) Calculate the equivalent mechanical forces (4-17) After the equivalent mechanical forces are calculated, they are added to the matrix and normal reductions are made to the loads.

List Superelements For list superelements, temperatures described by grid points are partitioned and assigned to BOTH the interior and exterior grids of each superelement the grid is associated to. Of course, this makes sense because the temperature loading is converted to the equivalent mechanical force on an elemental basis and the element must have the T for all of its nodes. Temperatures defined by elements are partitioned to the superelement the element belongs to.     Superelements and Modules User’s Guide Boundary Conditions in Static Analysis234 Main Index Note that MSC Nastran offers the user the flexibility of defining multiple constraints in the separate subcases of an analysis. This feature is not currently supported with superelements and if the user attempts to change the SPCs or MPCs between subcases, the following errors will occur:
    Listing 4-8 Error Message when User Attempt to Solve with Multiple Boundary Conditions Single Point Constraints (SPCs) Single Point Constraints (SPCs) are the fixed points in the solution. These can be defined with SPC, SPC1 , or on the GRID PS field. The SPC entries are activated with the SPC case control command, while the GRID PS field are always active.
    In addition to explicitly defined constraints, PARAM,AUTOSPC,YES will automatically constrain singular dof. For detailed information on PARAM,AUTOSPC refer to the Automatic Application of Single-Point Constraints (AUTOSPC) (Ch. 6) in the MSC Nastran Linear Static Analysis User’s Guide .
    List Superelements Constraints applied to points for List Superelements are partitioned in the same manner as the grid points. That is, constraints applied to interior points of a superelement are placed into the Bulk Data Section for that superelement and processed accordingly. If a grid is exterior to one superelement and interior to another, the constraint applied to the grid are ignored for the exterior grid and the constraint is applied to the interior grid of the most downstream superelement for that grid. PART Superelements As with List Superelements, the constraints on interior dof of a part superelement are processed with the superelement. However, constraints on exterior dof (i.e boundary grids) are carried down to the residual structure. When this occurs, the user is reminded with a clear message in the .f06 file: Listing 4-9 Info Message Issued Part Superelement Constraints are Applied to Boundary dof It is possible that either an explicit constraints or automatic constraints will be applied to a boundary grid.
    In this case, as long as the analysis coordinate frames (CD on the GRID entry) are congruent between the superelement components at the attachment grids, there is no problem. However, if the analysis coordinate frames are not congruent, the following error will be issued: ^^^ USER FATAL MESSAGE 9072 (PHASE0)

The external superelement process will automatically transform the external stiffness from its original coordinate frame to the residual coordinate frame. Boundary grids that have constraints should be applied in the downstream superelement. Grid Point Singularity Processing Because each superelement is processed independently, it is possible to turn AUTOSPC on and off, for each superelement (refer to section Parameter Controls below). Typically, AUTOSPC is applied to the entire model (all superelements). PARAM,AUTOSPC,YES is the default for all superelement solutions (except the nonlinear solutions). When the grid point singularity processor (AUTOSPC) is applied to superelements, MSC Nastran will only process the interior points of each superelement. Any points that are exterior to a superelement are defined as belonging to the A-set for that superelement. AUTOSPC will not constrain an A-set DOF . This logic makes sense because the exterior points of a superelement can have elements connected to them from other superelements; therefore, to constrain these points before we have a chance to attach all elements might over constrain the structure. AUTOSPC will process these grid points when processing the downstream superelement that contains them as interior points. Multipoint Constraints (MPCs) and Rigid Elements Multi Point Constraints (MPCs) define dof dependencies in the solution. These can be defined with MPC, RBAR, RBEi, RSPLINE, RTRPLT , or RSSCON . The rigid elements are automatically applied to every solution, whereas the MPCs must be activated with the MPC case control command. The parameter AUTOMSET can be used to rewrite the MPC equations to avoid set conflicts.
    PARAM,AUTOMSET ,YES is applicable to superelement analysis and will be processed in each superelement if requested by the user.
    List Superelements R-type elements (RBE2, RBE3, RBAR, RSSCON, etc.) in the main Bulk Data are treated as elements; i.e., their connectivity is used to determine which superelement partition the elements are assigned to. The rules to determine exterior points are the same as if these were flexible elements. ^^^

    Superelements and Modules User’s Guide Boundary Conditions in Static Analysis236 Main Index MPCs are not used to define superelement exterior points, so when they are near a boundary, the user may have to specify the exterior grids. Recall from Chapter 2 that element connectivity is used to determine the exterior points for a superelement. Because MPC sets are called in Case Control and different MPC sets can be used in each SUBCASE, MPC sets are not used in the definition of superelements. MPC entries are partitioned according to the interior points of superelements. An MPC entry is assigned to the highest upstream superelement (based on the processing order) to which it connects. Special care must be taken when an MPC or R-type element is connected to exterior points of a superelement. Because the exterior points are in the A-set for the superelement, these points cannot be listed as dependent (M-set) on an MPC or R-type element because a Set membership conflict will occur. Note that PARAM,AUTOMSET ,YES can often be used to resolve the set conflicts associated with dependent dof.
